initial_story: bias triangles represent features in stability diagrams of quantum dot (qd)devices, whose occurrence and property analysis are crucial indicators for spinphysics. nevertheless, challenges associated with quality and availability ofdata as well as the subtlety of physical phenomena of interest have hindered anautomatic and bespoke analysis framework, often still relying (in part) onhuman labelling and verification. we introduce a feature extraction frameworkfor bias triangles, built from unsupervised, segmentation-based computer visionmethods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification ofphysical properties of the former. thereby, the need for human input or largetraining datasets to inform supervised learning approaches is circumvented,while additionally enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and featurelabeling. in particular, we demonstrate that pauli spin blockade (psb)detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently and without any trainingdata as a direct result of this approach.
stories: In stability diagrams of quantum dot (QD) devices, bias triangles signify crucial features for spin physics investigation. However, the complexity of data acquisition and availability, coupled with the intricacy of related physical phenomena, has impeded the development of an automated and customized analysis system. Instead, we propose an unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision methodology for extracting bias triangle features. This approach allows for the direct identification and measurement of their physical properties without human intervention or extensive training datasets. Consequently, we showcase the feasibility of pauli spin blockade (PSB) detection using this method, which is efficient, effective, and requires no training data.

In the realm of quantum dot (QD) device stability diagrams, bias triangles play a pivotal role in investigations of spin physics. Despite their significance, the intricacies of data acquisition and the sophistication of the underlying physical phenomena have hindered the creation of an automated and tailored analysis system. Instead, we suggest employing an unsupervised, segmentation-methodology in computer vision for isolating bias triangle attributes. This strategy enables the immediate identification and quantification of their physical characteristics without human interference or extensive instructional datasets. Subsequently, we demonstrate the viability of detecting pauli spin blockade (PSB) with this technique, which boasts efficiency, effectiveness, and lacks any need for training data.

Although essential, the complexities of data collection and the intricate nature of the underlying physical processes have impeded the development of an automated and customized analysis tool. As an alternative, we propose implementing an unsupervised, segmentation-based approach in computer vision for distinguishing bias triangle attributes. This approach allows for the swift identification and measurement of their physical features without human intervention or extensive instructional data sets. We further illustrate the feasibility of detecting pauli spin blockade (PSB) using this technique, which offers advantages such as efficiency, effectiveness, and a lack of requirement for training data.
